entry.title: Do not use secure temp directory in browser tests
entry.content:
Normally, tests have their own scoped TMP directory set by the test

runner that is cleaned up after any test, including those that crash

or terminate prematurely.



However, when running tests as admin, the temp directory is pointed

to %systemroot%\SystemTemp instead of the value of TMP set by the

test runner.



This causes temp files to slowly build up in %systemroot%\SystemTemp,

which cannot be overridden by the test runner.



This CL changes browser tests (e.g. content_browsertests and

browser_tests) to instead use TMP environment variable for temporary

files instead of %systemroot%\SystemTemp so that these files can

be cleaned up



Since browser tests are intended to verify browser behavior and

the normal browser behavior is not running as an admin, I feel that

this change actually improves the match between test and reality

for theses types of tests.



BUG=1487776

entry.content:
This adds a new metric observer to count both UKM(a feature metric) and UMA for 3p cookie access(read&write) when 3PCD experiment is set to block 3P cookie. The third party cookie deprecation observer records the web feature counters, this help us to understand the impacts of 3PCD experiment with sample URLs and page loads.



The UMA metrics is help us to measure the unique clients and percentage of third party cookies access when 3PCD experiment is set to block 3P cookie.



These two metrics will be used to understand how third party cookie usage is on sites when 3PCD experiment is set to block 3P cookie

entry.title: Simplify ScrollbarThemeOverlayMobile/Mock color/size definitions
entry.content:
Previously we defined 3 sets of parameters:

1. In WebThemeEngineAndroid through GetScrollbarStyle(). The thumb width

and scrollbar margin were actually used through

ScrollbarThemeOverlayMobile, but the color was seldom (if ever) used

because we almost always composite scrollbars on Android. The color

defined there (SkColorSetARGB(128, 64, 64, 64)) was also different

from the actual scrollbar color (SkColor4f(0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5))

defined in blink's layer_tree_settings.cc.

2. In ScrollbarThemeOverlayMobile, as the values used in DevTools

mobile emulation. The values were different from those in

WebThemeEngineAndroid, causing different appearance of actual

Android scrollbars and the mobile emulated ones. The color

(0x80808080) was close to the actual color (see #1) but there were

some rounding errors between SkColor and SkColor4f.

3. In ScrollbarThemeOverlayMock. The color was defined there again

supposedly to be the same as the composited scrollbar color (see

#1) but has the same rounding error as #2.



Now define the color only in WebThemeEngineHelper::

AndroidScrollbarStyle() which is available for all builds, including

Android and platforms supporting DevTools mobile emulation and mock

overlay scrollbars. The color is still seldom used on Android, but

the next CL crrev.com/c/4968601 will combine the definition in blink

layer_tree_settings.cc into this one. This also makes the composited

and non-composited overlay scrollbars have the exact same color,

avoiding the needs of fuzzy match rule.

entry.title: Fix UBSan errors in wtf_unittests
entry.content:
Most of this is the C language bug where memcpy and friends cannot take

nullptr, even if length is zero. Elsewhere, I've been replacing them

with functions, which don't have this bug. But

is aware of the underlying type, while wtf/vector.h seems to have some

trait for types to opt out of the language-level constructor machinery.



I suspect all this (slightly unsafe) machinery could be made unnecessary

if we helped the optimizer out a bit more. E.g. if all the

memset/memcpy-compatible types made their trivial constructors and

trivial copy constructors visible to the header (counter to Chromium's

Clang plugin), the compiler would know that initializing them is trivial

and then emit the right code. But that's a much larger lift so, for now,

just skip memcpy if the span is empty.



And then atomic_operations_test.cc needs to be switched from

type-punning via pointer casts to type-punning via memcpy (here, memcpy

is the function we want) because the pointer casts are UB via strict

aliasing (disabled in Chromium) and additionally UB if the pointer is

not correctly aligned.

entry.title: pip-tuck: Add PipController
entry.content:
Currently there is no general controller for Picture-in-Picture (PiP)

windows. Having a dedicated controller for PiP windows would be useful

because:



1. There are multiple parts of the code that can be simplified by

introducing a controller that exists even when the PiP window does

not exist, without having to rely on `WindowState` which should be

reserved for more generic window functions. Examples include existing

`CompleteDrag()` animations and tucking behavior for PiP which we are

planning to implement.



2. A dedicated controller would allow for consolidation of the PiP

window management controls code.



This commit introduces the new class `PipController`, and also

transplants `UpdatePipBounds()` from `WindowState` to the new

`PipController`.



This new `PipController` holds a reference to the window it is managing

which can be obtained with `pip_window()`, and it is set with

`SetPipWindow()` and unset with `UnsetPipWindow()`. It also holds an

observer that observes this window when it is set.



Bug: b/305611254

The HDR10 overlay feature has some limitations, as itÂ 

may cause inconsistent tone mapping result andÂ lower

scrolling fps when in non-fullscreen mode, while the

feature could also reduce 3D usage to 0%Â when in

fullscreen mode, so we could only promoteÂ overlay

In summary, things that could promote HDR overlay success:



1. Device enabled system HDR feature.

3. DeviceÂ has P010 video processor support.

4. VideoÂ is in fullscreen mode.

entry.title: view-transition: Move pagereveal tests to WPT
entry.content:
The `pagereveal` event will be specified and shipped separately from

view transitions so move tests into WPT. Since the spec is still WIP

these tests are marked tentative for now.



Tests that were specifically dealing with usage of the `viewTransition`

attribute and its behavior in relation to a view transition were left in

the wpt_internal directory for view-transitions since those seems

specific to that feature.



Review note: PS#1 moves the files, diff from it to see changes.



These tests need to run in the no-forced-frame-update virtual test suite

since they're testing event order before rendering begins. WPT tests run

in single-threaded-mode which does not prevent scheduling frames before

rendering begins. This suite was added for other similar tests.



Additionally, there is a race during prerender activation between a

SynchronousComposite being called and receiving the WasShown signal from

the RenderWidgetHost. If the test invokes SynchronousComposite before

WasShown the BeginMainFrame is aborted. If a test is waiting on e.g. a

requestAnimationFrame it will timeout. This CL fixes this by detecting

this situation and scheduling a new frame when the widget becomes shown.

entry.title: Refactor InsetObserverView to use an explicit listener
entry.content:
InsetObserverView is currently broken because it purports to allow

consumption of insets, but uses View#onApplyWindowInsets. Overriding

View#onApplyWindowInsets doesn't work because the algorithm it uses

doesn't allow consumption ahead of a sibling[1] which is exactly what we

need to be able to do.



The compat version of the explicit listener lets us consume insets and

lets us unify on WindowInsetsCompat which enables some simplifications

and cleanups.



This CL also rectifies an issue where the insets animation callback wasn't being invoked because it wasn't set on the root view, which in practice seems to be necessary to receive this notification.



[1] https://cs.android.com/android/platform/superproject/main/+/main:frameworks/base/core/java/android/view/ViewGroup.java;l=7393

entry.title: Ensure TestHpkeKey calls EVP_HPKE_KEY_cleanup()
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, TestHpkeKey kept a raw EVP_HPKE_KEY, but failed to

call EVP_HPKE_KEY_cleanup() on destruction. This hasn't been a problem

yet because BoringSSL's implementation of EVP_HPKE_KEY_cleanup() is a

no-op, but it could lead to a memory leak if BoringSSL were to change

the implementation.



In more detail, this CL:

* Replaces TestHpkeKey's EVP_HPKE_KEY with a bssl::ScopedEVP_HPKE_KEY,

which automatically calls the cleanup function when it goes out of

scope.

* Moves the functionality of GenerateKey() into TestHpkeKey's

constructor.

* Changes TestHpkeKey into a move-only type.
